"# Chapter 8: Timbre & Envelope

*\"Two pianos can play the same note, and you still know which is which.\"*

---

You've built melodies, harmonies, and voices. But press middle C on a grand piano, then on an electric keyboard, then hum it — same pitch, same duration, wildly different *sound*. That difference is **timbre**: the color, the texture, the \"why does this sound like a clarinet and not a trumpet\" quality.

Chapter 7 gave you **section voices** — whole ensembles collapsed into a single playable instrument, their harmonic profiles tuned via `createPeriodicWave`. This chapter digs into the **how**: the envelope that shapes a note's life from birth to silence, the waveform that seeds its character, and the filters and detune spreads that make it *sing* or *growl* or *shimmer*.

We'll take **Twinkle Twinkle** — your companion melody since Chapter 3 — and **jazz it**. Not by changing the notes, but by changing *how they sound*: softening the attack, lengthening the release, spreading the detune, adding a little grit. Same melody, new wardrobe.

---

## 8.1 The Life of a Note: ADSR

Every note you've heard so far has an **envelope** — the curve of its loudness over time. You just haven't *chosen* one yet; the engine picked a default (a quick rise, a steady body, a quick fall). Now you will.

The standard envelope model is **ADSR**, four stages:

- **Attack** — how long it takes to reach full volume after you press the key. A piano has a fast attack (the hammer strikes instantly); a cello has a slower one (the bow takes a moment to bite the string).
- **Decay** — the initial drop after the peak. On a piano, the note is loudest the instant after the hammer hits, then fades slightly as the string settles.
- **Sustain** — the steady level while the key is held. This is a *level*, not a time. On a piano, sustain is silent (the note dies). On an organ, it's full volume (the key holds the pipe open).
- **Release** — how long it takes to fade to silence after you lift the key. A piano's release is the ring of the string after the damper falls. A synthesizer's can be instant (a click) or stretched (a wash).

[VISUAL: four-panel ADSR diagram — each panel shows one stage's curve overlaid on a waveform; panels stack left-to-right to show the full envelope shape. Attack rises, Decay drops to Sustain level, Sustain holds flat, Release falls to zero. Annotated with time on X-axis, amplitude on Y-axis. Curator-16 palette, dot-matrix render, clean line-graph clarity.]

```scheme
;; A note with a slow attack and long release — like a cello bowing in.
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* — ADSR control not yet exposed in the note surface.
(define (cello-note pitch dur velocity)
  (note/strike pitch dur velocity
               :attack 0.15   ;; 150ms to reach full volume
               :decay 0.05
               :sustain 0.8   ;; hold at 80% after decay
               :release 0.5)) ;; half-second ring after release

(cello-note 60 1.0 80) ;; middle C, one beat, medium velocity
```

<!-- BUILD: wire ADSR parameters into the note/strike verb; pass them through to the AudioParam envelope on the GainNode. Default: attack=0.01, decay=0.1, sustain=0.7, release=0.2 (the current implicit envelope). Validate that attack+decay+dur+release schedule correctly on the timeline. -->

*[needs: GAP-3]* — ADSR is a **gap**. The engine schedules notes, but the envelope shape isn't yet user-tunable. The example above shows the *interface* you're building toward; when GAP-3 closes, you'll be able to shape every note this way.

For now, trust the concept: **the envelope is the note's life story**. Fast attack + short release = percussive (piano, marimba). Slow attack + long release = legato (strings, voice, pads). The same pitch, two envelopes, two instruments.

---

## 8.2 Waveforms: The Seed of Timbre

Before the envelope shapes it, a note begins as a **waveform** — a repeating pattern of air pressure over time. You've been hearing sine waves (smooth, pure, flute-like). But there are others:

- **Sine** — one frequency, no overtones. Pure, glassy, a tuning fork.
- **Square** — odd harmonics (1st, 3rd, 5th, 7th…). Hollow, woody, a clarinet's lower register.
- **Sawtooth** — all harmonics (1st, 2nd, 3rd, 4th…). Bright, brassy, a violin bowing hard.
- **Triangle** — odd harmonics like square, but softer. Mellow, flute-ish, but richer than a sine.

[VISUAL: four waveforms rendered side-by-side — sine (smooth curve), square (sharp on/off), sawtooth (ramp up, sharp drop), triangle (linear rise and fall). Each one cycle shown, amplitude on Y, time on X. Dot-matrix, Curator-16, waveform lines in accent color against neutral background.]

The Web Audio API gives you oscillators with these four built-in types. You pick one, set its frequency (pitch), and it runs until you stop it.

```scheme
;; A square-wave note — hollow, reedy, like a clarinet.
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* — waveform selection not yet exposed.
(define (clarinet-note pitch dur velocity)
  (note/strike pitch dur velocity :waveform 'square))

(clarinet-note 60 1.0 80)
```

<!-- BUILD: add :waveform keyword to note/strike; map 'sine | 'square | 'sawtooth | 'triangle to oscillator.type; default 'sine. Validate that the oscillator type is set before the note schedules. -->

Each waveform has a **harmonic signature** — the mix of overtones riding on top of the fundamental frequency. A sine has none (just the one pure tone). A square has strong odd harmonics (the 3rd harmonic is 1/3 the amplitude of the fundamental, the 5th is 1/5, and so on). A sawtooth has *all* harmonics (each 1/n the amplitude). That's why a sawtooth sounds \"fuller\" than a square, and a square sounds \"richer\" than a sine.

Chapter 7's **section voices** are hand-tuned harmonic profiles built via `createPeriodicWave` — you specify exactly which harmonics at exactly which amplitudes. Waveforms are the *fast presets*: four common shapes, no tuning required.

---

## 8.3 Filters: Sculpting the Spectrum

A waveform gives you harmonics. A **filter** takes some away.

The most common filter is a **low-pass**: it lets low frequencies through and blocks high ones. Turn the **cutoff frequency** down, and the sound gets darker, duller, more muffled — like covering a speaker with a blanket. Turn it up, and the brightness returns.

[VISUAL: frequency spectrum graph — X-axis is frequency (20 Hz to 20 kHz, log scale), Y-axis is amplitude. Two overlays: (1) the full sawtooth spectrum (all harmonics, descending amplitude), (2) the same spectrum after a low-pass filter at 2 kHz — harmonics above 2 kHz are attenuated/removed. The cutoff is marked with a vertical line. Curator-16, dot-matrix, spectrum bars in one color, filtered result in another.]

```scheme
;; A filtered sawtooth — bright waveform, dark filter.
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* — filter control not yet exposed.
(define (muted-brass pitch dur velocity)
  (note/strike pitch dur velocity
               :waveform 'sawtooth
               :filter-type 'lowpass
               :filter-cutoff 1200)) ;; Hz — cuts above 1200

(muted-brass 60 1.0 80)
```

<!-- BUILD: add :filter-type and :filter-cutoff keywords to note/strike; wire to a BiquadFilterNode in the signal chain (oscillator → filter → gain → destination). Default: no filter (or an all-pass / very high cutoff). Validate cutoff range (20–20000 Hz reasonable). -->

Other filter types:

- **High-pass** — blocks lows, keeps highs. Makes the sound thin, tinny, like a telephone.
- **Band-pass** — keeps a slice in the middle, blocks lows and highs. Nasal, vocal-formant-like.
- **Notch** — cuts a slice in the middle, keeps lows and highs. Good for removing a hum or resonance.

Filters are **subtractive synthesis**: you start with a harmonically rich waveform (sawtooth, square) and carve away what you don't want. It's how analog synthesizers worked in the 1970s, and it's still the easiest way to get \"synth brass\" or \"synth strings\" — a bright wave, a dark filter, a slow envelope.

---

## 8.4 Detune Spread: The Shimmer

Play one note: clean. Play two notes a few cents apart (a **cent** is 1/100 of a semitone): they **beat** against each other, a slow wobble. Play a dozen notes spread across ±20 cents: they **shimmer**, a rich chorusing effect that makes one voice sound like many.

This is **detune spread**, and it's how you make a synthesizer sound *expensive*. Instead of one oscillator per note, you layer several, each slightly detuned, and the interference between them creates motion, width, life.

```scheme
;; A wide, shimmering pad — three oscillators per note, spread ±15 cents.
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* — detune spread / unison count not yet exposed.
(define (pad-note pitch dur velocity)
  (note/strike pitch dur velocity
               :waveform 'sawtooth
               :unison 3         ;; three oscillators
               :detune-spread 15)) ;; ±15 cents

(pad-note 60 2.0 70)
```

<!-- BUILD: add :unison (oscillator count, default 1) and :detune-spread (cents, default 0) keywords. For unison > 1, create N oscillators per note, detune them evenly across [-spread, +spread], sum their outputs (gain = 1/N to avoid clipping). Validate that detune is applied via oscillator.detune.value (in cents). -->

The **detune-spread** parameter is in **cents**. 100 cents = 1 semitone. Spread of 0 = no detune (one clean voice). Spread of 10–20 = subtle shimmer (good for pads, strings). Spread of 50+ = wide chorus (good for \"supersaw\" leads, detuned bells).

**Why it works:** when two sine waves are close in frequency, their peaks and troughs drift in and out of alignment. Where they align, the sound gets louder (constructive interference). Where they oppose, quieter (destructive interference). The result is a **beating** — a periodic rise and fall in volume. With many oscillators, each pair beats at a different rate, and the sum is a complex, evolving shimmer.

---

## 8.5 Jazz Envelope: Making Twinkle Swing

Now we put it together. **Twinkle Twinkle** has been your straight-backed companion since Chapter 3 — quarter notes on a piano, even and bright. Let's give it a jazz wardrobe:

- **Slow attack** — the note swells in, not hammered.
- **Long release** — each note rings into the next, a bit of overlap.
- **Sawtooth wave** — richer than a sine, but not as harsh as raw saw; we'll filter it.
- **Low-pass filter at 2400 Hz** — takes the edge off the brightness.
- **Subtle detune spread (±8 cents, 2 oscillators)** — just enough shimmer to suggest an ensemble, not a single instrument.

This is a **jazz piano voice** — warm, rounded, a bit smoky.

[VISUAL: staff notation of Twinkle Twinkle (first phrase, C C G G A A G), rendered with note-sprites (quarter notes, treble clef, 4/4 time). The note-sprites are bopping gently in place, eighth-note-tempo bop rate (since they're quarters). The runtime stands beside the staff, one hand conducting (small upbeat gesture), small smile. Curator-16, dot-matrix, staff lines in neutral, note-sprites in accent color.]

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* — full ADSR + waveform + filter + detune not yet wired.
;; This is the TARGET interface once the engine supports it.

(define (jazz-piano pitch dur velocity)
  (note/strike pitch dur velocity
               :waveform 'sawtooth
               :attack 0.08
               :decay 0.1
               :sustain 0.6
               :release 0.4
               :filter-type 'lowpass
               :filter-cutoff 2400
               :unison 2
               :detune-spread 8))

;; Twinkle Twinkle, first phrase, jazzed
(jazz-piano 60 1.0 75) ;; C
(jazz-piano 60 1.0 75) ;; C
(jazz-piano 67 1.0 75) ;; G
(jazz-piano 67 1.0 75) ;; G
(jazz-piano 69 1.0 75) ;; A
(jazz-piano 69 1.0 75) ;; A
(jazz-piano 67 2.0 75) ;; G (half note)
```

<!-- BUILD: when GAP-3 closes, validate this example end-to-end — all parameters honored, envelope + filter + detune + waveform sounding as specified. Save the resulting tape as \"twinkle-jazzed-phrase-1.wav\" for the training corpus. -->

The melody is **unchanged** — same pitches, same rhythm. But the *timbre* transforms it. The slow attack softens the entrance of each note (less \"plunk,\" more \"breath\"). The long release makes the notes overlap slightly, a gentle legato. The filtered sawtooth gives it body without harshness. The detune spread adds a subtle shimmer, as if two pianists are playing in near-unison, their tunings just a hair apart.

This is **additive expressiveness**. You didn't rewrite the melody. You didn't add ornaments (that's Chapter 12). You changed *how it sounds*, and the melody became something new.

---

## 8.6 The Full Twinkle, Jazzed

Let's finish the tune. Two phrases, each shaped with the jazz-piano voice.

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* — ADSR + waveform + filter + detune awaiting engine surface.

(define (jazz-piano pitch dur velocity)
  (note/strike pitch dur velocity
               :waveform 'sawtooth
               :attack 0.08
               :decay 0.1
               :sustain 0.6
               :release 0.4
               :filter-type 'lowpass
               :filter-cutoff 2400
               :unison 2
               :detune-spread 8))

;; Phrase 1
(jazz-piano 60 1.0 75) ;; Twin-
(jazz-piano 60 1.0 75) ;; kle
(jazz-piano 67 1.0 75) ;; twin-
(jazz-piano 67 1.0 75) ;; kle
(jazz-piano 69 1.0 75) ;; lit-
(jazz-piano 69 1.0 75) ;; tle
(jazz-piano 67 2.0 75) ;; star

;; Phrase 2
(jazz-piano 65 1.0 75) ;; How I
(jazz-piano 65 1.0 75) ;; won-
(jazz-piano 64 1.0 75) ;; der
(jazz-piano 64 1.0 75) ;; what you
(jazz-piano 62 1.0 75) ;; are
(jazz-piano 62 1.0 75) ;;
(jazz-piano 60 2.0 75) ;; (fermata)
```

<!-- BUILD: validate full Twinkle with jazz-piano voice once GAP-3 closes. Save as \"twinkle-jazzed-full.wav\". Compare to the straight piano version from Ch3 to confirm the timbral difference is audible and intentional. -->

The same notes you played in Chapter 3, now wearing a different suit. The melody hasn't changed, but the *sound* has — warmer, rounder, a bit of shimmer and swell. That's timbre working.

[VISUAL: split-screen comparison — left side shows the Ch3 piano staff (Twinkle, plain quarter notes, bright/sharp waveform sketch above it), right side shows the Ch8 jazz-piano staff (same notation, but filtered sawtooth waveform sketch above it, visibly softer/darker spectrum). Both staves have bopping note-sprites. The runtime in the center, one hand toward each side, as if presenting the before/after. Curator-16, dot-matrix.]

