### 8.15 Micro-Timing: Humanizing the Attack

Real players don't strike notes at *exactly* the same instant. A pianist's fingers land a few milliseconds apart. A horn section breathes together but not in perfect sync. This tiny **jitter** (±5–20ms) is what makes a programmed performance feel **human** instead of robotic.

```scheme
;; Perfectly synchronized (robotic)
(define (robot-chord pitches dur)
  (for-each
    (lambda (pitch)
      (note/strike pitch dur 0.7))
    pitches))

;; Humanized: each note offset by a small random jitter
(define (human-chord pitches dur)
  (for-each
    (lambda (pitch)
      (let ((jitter (/ (random 20) 1000.0)))  ;; 0–20ms
        (sleep jitter)
        (note/strike pitch dur 0.7)))
    pitches))

(robot-chord '(C4 E4 G4))
(sleep 2)
(human-chord '(C4 E4 G4))
```

`<!-- BUILD: compare robotic (simultaneous) vs. humanized (jittered) chord -->`

The humanized chord feels **warmer, more alive** — even though the jitter is barely perceptible, your ear knows.

---


### 8.16 Tremolo: Amplitude Modulation

**Tremolo** is a *rhythmic wavering in volume* — like a guitarist's thumb on the volume knob, or a violinist's bow pressure pulsing. It's **amplitude modulation** (AM): the note's loudness oscillates at a low frequency (3–8 Hz).

*[needs: GAP-3]* — tremolo requires **gain modulation** on the note:

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* — tremolo (AM) not yet wired
(note/strike 'A4 'whole 0.7
  :tremolo-rate 5   ;; Hz — the volume wobbles 5 times per second
  :tremolo-depth 0.4) ;; 40% modulation depth
```

`<!-- BUILD: add :tremolo-rate and :tremolo-depth params → modulate GainNode with a low-frequency oscillator (LFO) -->`

[VISUAL: Waveform of a sustained note with a visible \"wavy\" amplitude envelope — the peaks and troughs repeat rhythmically, like ocean waves.]

Tremolo is a staple of **surf rock guitar**, **gospel organ**, and **romantic string sections**.

---


### 8.17 Vibrato: Frequency Modulation

**Vibrato** is a *rhythmic wavering in pitch* — a singer's or violinist's slight wobble around the target note. It's **frequency modulation** (FM): the pitch oscillates at 4–7 Hz, ±5–15 cents.

*[needs: GAP-3]* — vibrato requires **pitch modulation**:

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* — vibrato (FM) not yet wired
(note/strike 'G4 'whole 0.7
  :vibrato-rate 6     ;; Hz
  :vibrato-depth 10)  ;; cents
```

`<!-- BUILD: add :vibrato-rate and :vibrato-depth params → modulate OscillatorNode.detune with an LFO -->`

[VISUAL: A sine wave with a visible \"wiggle\" in the frequency axis — the peaks are slightly closer together, then farther apart, rhythmically. A label: \"Vibrato — pitch wobble.\"]

Vibrato makes a note feel **sung, expressive, alive** — no human voice or bowed string holds a pitch perfectly still.

---


### 8.18 Combined Modulation: Tremolo + Vibrato

Many expressive instruments (voice, strings, vintage organs) use **both** tremolo and vibrato simultaneously. The result is **richer, more organic** than either alone.

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]*
(note/strike 'D4 'whole 0.75
  :tremolo-rate 5 :tremolo-depth 0.3
  :vibrato-rate 6 :vibrato-depth 8)
```

`<!-- BUILD: combined AM + FM modulation -->`

The note **sways and pulses** — it sounds almost like it's breathing.

---


### 8.19 Portamento: Sliding Between Pitches

**Portamento** (or **glissando**) is a *continuous pitch slide* from one note to the next — a trombone's smooth glide, a theremin's eerie sweep, a synth lead's legato run.

*[needs: GAP-3]* — portamento requires **pitch ramping**:

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* — portamento not yet wired
(note/strike 'C4 'quarter 0.7)
(note/strike 'G4 'quarter 0.7
  :portamento 0.3)  ;; 300ms slide from the previous note's pitch
```

`<!-- BUILD: add :portamento param → use exponentialRampToValueAtTime on OscillatorNode.frequency to glide from the prior note -->`

[VISUAL: Two notes on a staff (C4 and G4) connected by a diagonal line (the portamento marking). A graph below showing frequency rising smoothly from C4 to G4 over 300ms.]

Portamento is the signature of **synth leads, fretless bass, and vocal runs**.

---


### 8.20 The Attack \"Snap\": Adding a Transient Click

Percussive instruments (piano, marimba, tabla) have a **transient** — a brief, bright **click or snap** at the very start of the note, caused by the hammer strike or stick impact. This transient is *higher in frequency* and *much shorter* than the note itself, but it's crucial for **clarity and punch**.

You can model it by **layering a short, bright noise burst** at the note onset:

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* — transient layering
(define (percussive-note pitch dur vel)
  ;; The main note
  (note/strike pitch dur vel
    :attack 0.01 :decay 0.2 :sustain 0.3 :release 0.1)
  
  ;; The transient: a 5ms noise burst
  (sfx 'click :duration 0.005 :velocity (* vel 0.5)))

(percussive-note 'C5 'quarter 0.8)
```

`<!-- BUILD: layer a short noise transient atop the note for percussive \"snap\" -->`

The transient is what makes a note feel **struck** rather than **blown** or **bowed**.

---


### 8.21 Ensemble Spread: Slight Timing + Tuning Variation Across Voices

A real string section (10 violins) never plays in *perfect* unison. Each player:
- **Starts the note a few milliseconds off** from the others.
- **Is tuned a few cents sharp or flat** relative to concert pitch.
- **Has a slightly different vibrato rate and depth**.

This **ensemble spread** is what makes an orchestral section sound **rich and huge** instead of like one violin copy-pasted ten times.

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]*
(define (string-section pitch dur)
  (let ((players 8))
    (for-each
      (lambda (i)
        (let ((jitter (/ (random 15) 1000.0))       ;; 0–15ms timing offset
              (detune (- (random 8) 4))             ;; ±4 cents tuning
              (vib-rate (+ 5.5 (/ (random 10) 10.0))) ;; 5.5–6.5 Hz vibrato
              (vib-depth (+ 6 (random 4))))         ;; 6–10 cents depth
          (sleep jitter)
          (note/strike pitch dur 0.5
            :attack 0.15 :decay 0.1 :sustain 0.75 :release 0.8
            :detune detune
            :vibrato-rate vib-rate
            :vibrato-depth vib-depth)))
      (iota players))))

(string-section 'A4 'whole)
```

`<!-- BUILD: ensemble spread demo — 8 slightly offset, detuned, vibrato-varied notes -->`

[VISUAL: Eight violin sprites arranged in a section (stage left). Each has a tiny number above it (1–8). Below, a graph showing 8 slightly staggered note-onset lines (not all starting at the same instant) and 8 wavy pitch-modulation traces (each vibrato slightly different).]

This is the sound of a **real section** — human, imperfect, alive.

---


### 8.22 A Walking Jazz Bassline with Envelope Variation

Jazz bass is **percussive but warm**: short notes, each with a moderate attack and quick release, but not so sharp that they feel mechanical. Each note's envelope can vary slightly — a real bassist doesn't strike every note identically.

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]*
(define (jazz-bass-note pitch dur)
  (let ((attack (+ 0.015 (/ (random 10) 1000.0)))  ;; 15–25ms attack
        (release (+ 0.08 (/ (random 20) 1000.0)))) ;; 80–100ms release
    (note/strike pitch dur 0.7
      :attack attack
      :decay 0.05
      :sustain 0.2
      :release release
      :filter 'lowpass
      :cutoff 1200)))

;; A four-bar walking bassline in C
(define (walking-bass)
  (jazz-bass-note 'C2 'quarter)
  (jazz-bass-note 'E2 'quarter)
  (jazz-bass-note 'G2 'quarter)
  (jazz-bass-note 'A2 'quarter)
  
  (jazz-bass-note 'F2 'quarter)
  (jazz-bass-note 'A2 'quarter)
  (jazz-bass-note 'C3 'quarter)
  (jazz-bass-note 'D3 'quarter)
  
  (jazz-bass-note 'G2 'quarter)
  (jazz-bass-note 'B2 'quarter)
  (jazz-bass-note 'D3 'quarter)
  (jazz-bass-note 'E3 'quarter)
  
  (jazz-bass-note 'C2 'quarter)
  (jazz-bass-note 'E2 'quarter)
  (jazz-bass-note 'G2 'quarter)
  (jazz-bass-note 'C3 'quarter))

(walking-bass)
```

`<!-- BUILD: walking bassline with per-note envelope variation -->`

Each note has a **slightly different attack and release** — it sounds like a human hand, not a sequencer.

