### 8.27 A Bell: Instant Attack, Inharmonic Partials, Very Long Release

Church bells and tubular bells have **inharmonic overtones** (the partials are *not* integer multiples of the fundamental) and a **very long decay** (seconds to minutes).

*[needs: GAP-4]* — true inharmonic partials require custom `PeriodicWave` profiles. We can approximate with:

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* (envelope) + *[needs: GAP-4]* (inharmonic partials)
(define (bell pitch dur)
  (note/strike pitch dur 0.7
    :attack 0.001
    :decay 3.0       ;; three-second decay
    :sustain 0.0
    :release 0.01
    ;; Inharmonic partials would be defined via createPeriodicWave,
    ;; e.g., partials at [1.0, 2.3, 3.9, 5.1, ...] not [1, 2, 3, 4, ...]
    ))

(bell 'C4 'whole)
```

`<!-- BUILD: envelope approximation; true bell timbre requires GAP-4 PeriodicWave with inharmonic ratios -->`

[VISUAL: A large church bell (bronze, hanging). A waveform below showing an instant spike (attack) and a *very* slow exponential decay (the tail lasts many seconds).]

---


### 8.28 A Timpani Roll: Rapid Repeated Strikes with Slight Pitch Bend

A timpani roll is **not a single sustained note** — it's **many rapid strikes** (10–20 per second), each with a short envelope. Often the player will **bend the pitch slightly** during the roll by adjusting the pedal.

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* (portamento for pitch bend)
(define (timpani-strike pitch vel)
  (note/strike pitch 'thirty-second vel
    :attack 0.005
    :decay 0.08
    :sustain 0.0
    :release 0.02
    :filter 'lowpass
    :cutoff 600))

(define (timpani-roll pitch dur strikes)
  (let ((interval (/ dur strikes)))
    (for-each
      (lambda (i)
        (let ((vel (+ 0.6 (/ (random 20) 100.0))))  ;; 0.6–0.8
          (timpani-strike pitch vel)
          (sleep interval)))
      (iota strikes))))

;; A two-second roll on C2, ~16 strikes
(timpani-roll 'C2 2.0 16)
```

`<!-- BUILD: timpani roll via rapid repeated strikes -->`

The result is a **low, rumbling growl** — percussive but sustained.

---


### 8.29 Velocity Layers: Different Samples for Soft vs. Hard Strikes

High-end virtual instruments use **velocity layers**: different recordings (or synthesis profiles) for soft, medium, and hard strikes. A soft piano note has a *fundamentally different harmonic spectrum* than a hard one — not just lower amplitude.

Model this with **discrete envelope + filter profiles per velocity range**:

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]*
(define (layered-piano pitch dur vel)
  (cond
    ;; Soft layer (vel < 0.4)
    ((< vel 0.4)
     (note/strike pitch dur vel
       :attack 0.08 :decay 0.3 :sustain 0.5 :release 0.6
       :filter 'lowpass :cutoff 1200))
    
    ;; Medium layer (0.4 ≤ vel < 0.7)
    ((< vel 0.7)
     (note/strike pitch dur vel
       :attack 0.03 :decay 0.25 :sustain 0.4 :release 0.5
       :filter 'lowpass :cutoff 2000))
    
    ;; Hard layer (vel ≥ 0.7)
    (else
     (note/strike pitch dur vel
       :attack 0.01 :decay 0.2 :sustain 0.3 :release 0.4
       :filter 'lowpass :cutoff 3200))))

;; Same note, three velocities
(layered-piano 'C4 'half 0.3)
(sleep 1.5)
(layered-piano 'C4 'half 0.55)
(sleep 1.5)
(layered-piano 'C4 'half 0.85)
```

`<!-- BUILD: velocity-layer demo -->`

Each layer sounds **qualitatively different**, not just louder or softer.

---


### 8.30 The \"Breath\" Noise: Adding Air to Wind Instruments

Wind instruments (flute, sax, oboe) have **breath noise** — a soft, high-frequency hiss mixed with the tonal component. This noise is **part of the sound**, not a flaw.

You can add it by **layering a filtered noise burst** atop the note:

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* + noise source
(define (breathy-flute pitch dur vel)
  ;; The tonal component
  (note/strike pitch dur vel
    :attack 0.1 :decay 0.05 :sustain 0.8 :release 0.3
    :filter 'lowpass :cutoff 2400
    :vibrato-rate 5 :vibrato-depth 6)
  
  ;; The breath noise (filtered white noise, quieter than the tone)
  (sfx 'wind :duration dur :velocity (* vel 0.15) :filter 'highpass :cutoff 2000))

(breathy-flute 'A4 'whole 0.6)
```

`<!-- BUILD: layer filtered noise atop tonal note for \"breath\" character -->`

The result is **airy, organic, human** — you hear the player's breath.

---


### 8.31 Flanging: A Sweeping Comb Filter

**Flanging** is a time-based effect: a delayed copy of the signal is mixed with the original, and the delay time is **modulated** (swept). This creates a **sweeping comb-filter** sound — a series of moving notches in the spectrum.

*[needs: GAP-3]* — flanging requires a **delay line + modulated delay time**:

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* — flanging not yet wired
(note/strike 'D4 'whole 0.7
  :flanger-rate 0.5   ;; Hz — the sweep speed
  :flanger-depth 0.008) ;; seconds — the delay-time modulation range
```

`<!-- BUILD: add flanging effect via DelayNode + LFO modulating delayTime -->`

[VISUAL: A spectrogram showing diagonal \"comb\" patterns sweeping up and down through the frequency range — the notches moving in time.]

Flanging is a staple of **psychedelic rock, synthwave, and jet-plane sound effects**.

---


### 8.32 A Slow Swell: Zero Attack Volume, Long Fade-In

Some synthesizer patches (and orchestral swells) start from **complete silence** and fade in over many seconds — the **reverse** of a normal envelope.

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]*
(define (reverse-swell pitch dur)
  (note/strike pitch dur 0.7
    :attack (* dur 0.8)  ;; 80% of the note's duration is the attack
    :decay 0.0
    :sustain 1.0
    :release (* dur 0.2)))

(reverse-swell 'Bb3 4.0)
```

`<!-- BUILD: reverse-swell envelope -->`

The sound **emerges from nothing, swells to full, then fades** — cinematic, ambient, huge.

---


### 8.33 A Detuned Unison Lead: The \"Supersaw\" Single Note

The classic **trance lead** sound is a *single melodic line* where each note is a thick stack of detuned oscillators:

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]*
(define (trance-lead pitch dur)
  (let ((detunes '(-18 -12 -6 0 6 12 18)))  ;; wide spread
    (for-each
      (lambda (dt)
        (note/strike pitch dur 0.4
          :attack 0.05
          :decay 0.15
          :sustain 0.7
          :release 0.5
          :detune dt
          :filter 'lowpass
          :cutoff 3500
          :resonance 4))
      detunes)))

;; A simple melodic phrase
(define (trance-phrase)
  (trance-lead 'E4 'quarter)
  (trance-lead 'G4 'quarter)
  (trance-lead 'B4 'quarter)
  (trance-lead 'D5 'eighth)
  (trance-lead 'E5 'eighth)
  (trance-lead 'G5 'half))

(trance-phrase)
```

`<!-- BUILD: trance-lead demo -->`

The lead is **huge, shimmering, almost choral** — seven oscillators per note.

---


### 8.34 A Sub-Bass: Pure Sine, No Harmonics, Very Low

**Sub-bass** (common in dubstep, trap, and drum-and-bass) is a *pure sine wave* at 40–80 Hz — no overtones, no envelope complexity, just a **felt low-frequency rumble**.

```scheme
(define (sub-bass pitch dur)
  (note/strike pitch dur 0.9
    :attack 0.01
    :decay 0.0
    :sustain 1.0
    :release 0.05
    :waveform 'sine))  ;; pure sine, no harmonics

(sub-bass 'C1 'whole)
```

`<!-- BUILD: sub-bass (pure sine, low freq) -->`

You don't *hear* the sub-bass as a pitch — you **feel it** in your chest. It's the foundation under everything else.

---


### 8.35 A Distorted Lead: Soft Clipping for Grit

**Distortion** (or **overdrive**) adds harmonics by **clipping** the waveform — pushing the amplitude beyond the normal range and flattening the peaks. This creates a **gritty, aggressive, \"dirty\"** sound.

*[needs: GAP-3]* — distortion requires a **waveshaper** or **gain overdrive**:

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* — waveshaper distortion not yet wired
(note/strike 'E2 'quarter 0.95
  :distortion 0.7  ;; 0.0 = clean, 1.0 = heavy clipping
  :filter 'lowpass
  :cutoff 2000)
```

`<!-- BUILD: add :distortion param → apply WaveShaperNode with a soft-clipping curve -->`

[VISUAL: Two waveforms side-by-side. Left: clean sine (smooth curves). Right: distorted (the peaks and troughs are flattened, the curve is \"squared off\"). Label: \"Distortion adds harmonics.\"]

Distortion is the sound of **rock guitar, fuzzed bass, and aggressive synth leads**.

---


### 8.36 A Reversed Note: The Swell Starts Loud, Ends Quiet

A **reversed envelope** (loud → quiet instead of quiet → loud) creates an eerie, unnatural effect — common in ambient and cinematic music.

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]*
(define (reversed-note pitch dur)
  (note/strike pitch dur 0.9
    :attack 0.001     ;; instant start at full volume
    :decay (* dur 0.9)  ;; long decay (most of the note)
    :sustain 0.0
    :release 0.01))

(reversed-note 'F#4 'whole)
```

`<!-- BUILD: reversed envelope demo -->`

The note **starts loud and fades to silence** — the opposite of natural sound, but musically compelling.

---


### 8.37 A Lo-Fi Crackle: Adding Noise to the Envelope

**Lo-fi** music (vaporwave, chillhop) often has **vinyl crackle** or **tape hiss** — a layer of noise that makes the sound feel **old, degraded, nostalgic**.

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* + continuous noise layer
(define (lofi-note pitch dur vel)
  ;; The main note
  (note/strike pitch dur vel
    :attack 0.05 :decay 0.2 :sustain 0.5 :release 0.3
    :filter 'lowpass :cutoff 2200)
  
  ;; The crackle (quiet noise, same duration)
  (sfx 'static :duration dur :velocity 0.05 :filter 'highpass :cutoff 3000))

(lofi-note 'Eb4 'half 0.6)
```

`<!-- BUILD: layer quiet noise atop note for lo-fi crackle -->`

The result is **warm, degraded, emotionally \"vintage\"** — even though it's synthesized.

---


### 8.38 A Metallic Percussion: Inharmonic, Bright, Fast Decay

Metallic percussion (cymbals, gongs, triangles) has **inharmonic partials** and a **very bright, clangy** timbre.

*[needs: GAP-4]* — true metallic timbre requires inharmonic PeriodicWave. Approximate with:

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* (envelope) + *[needs: GAP-4]* (inharmonic partials)
(define (metallic-hit pitch dur)
  (note/strike pitch dur 0.85
    :attack 0.001
    :decay 0.8
    :sustain 0.0
    :release 0.01
    :filter 'highpass
    :cutoff 1500
    :resonance 5))  ;; high resonance for \"ring\"

(metallic-hit 'G5 'quarter)
```

`<!-- BUILD: bright, resonant, fast-decay envelope approximation -->`

The sound is **sharp, shimmering, metallic** — you hear the \"clang.\"

---


### 8.39 A Formant Filter: The \"Vowel\" Sound

Human vowels (ah, eh, ee, oh, oo) are created by **formants** — resonant peaks in the vocal tract's frequency response. A **formant filter** can make a synthesizer \"sing\" vowel sounds.

*[needs: GAP-3]* — formant filtering requires **multiple bandpass filters** tuned to specific frequencies:

```scheme
;; *[needs: GAP-3]* — formant filter not yet wired
(note/strike 'A3 'whole 0.7
  :formant 'ah)  ;; presets: 'ah 'eh 'ee 'oh 'oo
```

`<!-- BUILD: add :formant param → chain multiple BiquadFilterNodes (bandpass) at vowel-specific frequencies -->`

[VISUAL: A spectrum analyzer showing two or three sharp peaks (the formants) at specific frequencies — e.g., for \"ah,\" peaks at ~700Hz and ~1200Hz.]

The note sounds like a **choir singing \"ah\"** — synthetic but unmistakably vocal.

