### 8.6  A swing rhythm — articulation via envelope

Jazz isn't just timbre—it's also *rhythm* and *articulation*. Swing rhythm (covered more in Ch10—polyrhythm) is a triplet subdivision where the first note of the triplet is held longer than the second (roughly 2:1). But even in straight time, jazz articulation uses **short, detached notes** for comping chords and **longer, sustained notes** for melody.

Let's play a simple I–vi–ii–V progression (C–Am–Dm–G) with short, detached chords (staccato envelope) and a melody with longer sustain.

```scheme
;; Staccato envelope for comping chords: very short sustain, quick release.
(define staccato-piano
  (let ((v (voice/create 'staccato-piano)))
    (voice/waveform v (createPeriodicWave (list 1.0 0.5 0.3 0.15 0.08)))
    (voice/envelope v (adsr 0.01 0.05 0.1 0.05))  ;; fast decay, low sustain, quick release
    (voice/filter v 'lowpass 3500 0.7)
    v))

;; Legato envelope for melody: longer sustain, slower release.
(define legato-piano
  (let ((v (voice/create 'legato-piano)))
    (voice/waveform v (createPeriodicWave (list 1.0 0.5 0.3 0.15 0.08)))
    (voice/envelope v (adsr 0.02 0.1 0.6 0.2))   ;; moderate decay, higher sustain, longer release
    (voice/filter v 'lowpass 3500 0.7)
    v))

;; Progression: I–vi–ii–V in C, quarter-note chords, staccato.
;; Measure 1: C (C3 E3 G3)
(note/strike 'C3 'quarter 0.6 staccato-piano)
(note/strike 'E3 'quarter 0.6 staccato-piano)
(note/strike 'G3 'quarter 0.6 staccato-piano)

;; Measure 2: Am (A2 C3 E3)
(at-beat 4
  (note/strike 'A2 'quarter 0.6 staccato-piano)
  (note/strike 'C3 'quarter 0.6 staccato-piano)
  (note/strike 'E3 'quarter 0.6 staccato-piano))

;; Measure 3: Dm (D3 F3 A3)
(at-beat 8
  (note/strike 'D3 'quarter 0.6 staccato-piano)
  (note/strike 'F3 'quarter 0.6 staccato-piano)
  (note/strike 'A3 'quarter 0.6 staccato-piano))

;; Measure 4: G (G2 B2 D3)
(at-beat 12
  (note/strike 'G2 'quarter 0.6 staccato-piano)
  (note/strike 'B2 'quarter 0.6 staccato-piano)
  (note/strike 'D3 'quarter 0.6 staccato-piano))

;; Melody over the progression (legato): C4 D4 E4 D4 C4 (half, quarter, quarter, quarter, half).
(note/strike 'C4 'half 0.7 legato-piano)
(at-beat 2 (note/strike 'D4 'quarter 0.7 legato-piano))
(at-beat 3 (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 0.7 legato-piano))
(at-beat 4 (note/strike 'D4 'quarter 0.7 legato-piano))
(at-beat 5 (note/strike 'C4 'half 0.7 legato-piano))
```

<!-- BUILD: run this as a complete cart; verify staccato chords are clipped short and melody notes sustain smoothly -->

**What you hear:** The chords are short and detached—**comp** chords, the harmonic bed. The melody floats above with longer, connected notes—**legato** phrasing. This is the envelope doing the articulation work.

**Try this:**
- Flip the envelopes—give the chords the legato envelope and the melody the staccato. It sounds awkward: the chords blur into each other (muddy), and the melody loses its line.
- Make the staccato envelope even shorter: `(adsr 0.01 0.03 0.05 0.03)`. Now the chords are almost percussive stabs, like a rim-shot on a snare.

[VISUAL: Two staves, treble and bass clef. Bass: quarter-note chords (C, Am, Dm, G), each chord shown as a vertical stack of three notes with small staccato dots above (meaning \"short\"). Treble: melody line (C4 D4 E4 D4 C4) with slurs connecting them (meaning \"smooth\"). Note-sprites (16×16) bob on both staves, faster bops for staccato, slower for legato.]

---


### 8.7  Vibrato — modulating pitch over time

Vibrato is a *periodic variation in pitch*—a slight wobble, usually 5–7 Hz (5–7 wobbles per second), ±10–30 cents. It's not an envelope (amplitude over time); it's **pitch modulation**. Singers do it naturally. String players do it with finger motion. Synthesizers do it with an LFO (low-frequency oscillator) modulating the frequency.

We can apply vibrato globally to a voice, or per-note. For now, let's do it globally (per-note vibrato control is *[needs: GAP-3]*).

```scheme
;; A legato voice with vibrato: 6 Hz wobble, ±15 cents depth.
(define vibrato-voice
  (let ((v (voice/create 'vibrato-voice)))
    (voice/waveform v (createPeriodicWave (list 1.0 0.5 0.3 0.15)))
    (voice/envelope v (adsr 0.05 0.1 0.8 0.3))
    (voice/vibrato v 6.0 15.0)  ;; 6 Hz rate, 15 cents depth
    v))

;; Play a sustained A4 for 2 beats.
(note/strike 'A4 'half 0.75 vibrato-voice)
```
*[needs: GAP-3]* — vibrato as a separate modulation control.

<!-- BUILD: voice/vibrato setter that creates an LFO (OscillatorNode at 6 Hz) modulating the main oscillator's frequency.detune param -->

**What you hear:** The note doesn't sit still—it wobbles gently up and down in pitch, like a singer or a violinist. Too fast (12 Hz) and it sounds like a siren. Too slow (2 Hz) and it sounds like poor intonation.

**Try this:**
- Set the depth to 5 cents—very subtle, almost imperceptible, but it adds \"life.\"
- Set the depth to 50 cents—way too wide, it sounds like a bent note or a theremin.
- Use vibrato on a chord (three notes struck together)—all three wobble together, which is unrealistic (real string players don't sync their vibrato). This is why vibrato is often applied per-note, not per-voice. *[needs: GAP-3]*

[VISUAL: A pitch-over-time graph showing a horizontal line (the target pitch, A4=440 Hz) with a sine wave wobbling ±15 cents around it. A note-sprite (half note, 48×48) sits at the start, bopping slowly as the vibrato cycles.]

