### 8.16  Dynamic envelope shaping — velocity-sensitive attack

On a real piano, **velocity** (how hard you hit the key) affects not just volume, but also *timbre*: a hard strike has a sharper attack and brighter harmonics (more high-frequency content from the hammer impact). We can simulate this by making the envelope's attack time and the filter cutoff *velocity-sensitive*.

Let's play the same pitch three times at different velocities, and adjust the attack and brightness accordingly.

```scheme
;; Velocity-sensitive piano voice.
(define (make-vel-piano velocity)
  (let ((v (voice/create 'vel-piano))
        ;; Attack time inversely proportional to velocity: soft = slow, hard = fast.
        (attack-time (- 0.1 (* velocity 0.08)))  ;; 0.02s at vel=1.0, 0.1s at vel=0.0
        ;; Filter cutoff proportional to velocity: soft = dark, hard = bright.
        (cutoff (+ 1000 (* velocity 4000))))     ;; 1000 Hz at vel=0.0, 5000 Hz at vel=1.0
    (voice/waveform v (createPeriodicWave (list 1.0 0.5 0.3 0.2 0.1)))
    (voice/envelope v (adsr attack-time 0.15 0.4 0.1))
    (voice/filter v 'lowpass cutoff 0.7)
    v))

;; Play C4 at three velocities: soft (0.3), medium (0.6), hard (0.9).
(note/strike 'C4 'quarter 0.3 (make-vel-piano 0.3))
(at-beat 1 (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 0.6 (make-vel-piano 0.6)))
(at-beat 2 (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 0.9 (make-vel-piano 0.9)))
```

<!-- BUILD: run and verify the three notes sound progressively brighter and snappier -->

**What you hear:** The first note is soft, dark, and slow to grab. The second is brighter and quicker. The third is very bright and percussive—almost a different instrument.

**Try this:**
- Exaggerate the effect: make the attack at vel=0.0 be 0.5s (very slow), and the cutoff at vel=1.0 be 8000 Hz (very bright).
- Apply this to a melody and vary the velocity on each note—some notes are soft and warm, others are bright and accented.

[VISUAL: Three waveforms side-by-side, each showing the same pitch (C4) but with different envelope shapes. Left (soft): slow rise, dark. Middle (medium): moderate. Right (hard): sharp spike, bright. Note-sprites (quarter notes, 16×16) sit on each, labeled with velocity values (0.3, 0.6, 0.9).]

